  </equation><para id="import-auto-id1211554">where <emphasis effect="italics"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{d} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></emphasis> is the distance from A to B, or the distance between the plates in <link target-id="import-auto-id671952"/>. Note that the above equation implies the units for electric field are volts per meter. We already know the units for electric field are newtons per coulomb; thus the following relation among units is valid:</para><equation id="eip-847"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>1 N</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo><m:mn>C</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mtext>1 V</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo><m:mn>m</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"1 N"/C="1 V"/m} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation><note id="fs-id1540577"><label/><title>Voltage between Points A and B</title>
